Consider the following graph. What is the equation of the parabola?

generalfeedback.text: Recall that the roots of the quadratic correcpond to the \(x\)-intercepts of the graph, therefore the roots are \[ x = -6 \qquad \mbox{and} \qquad x = 3 \] Hence the quadratic has the form \[ y = a\cdot (x+6)(x-3) \] Now substituting \(x = 0\) and \(y = -18\) and rearranging for \(a\) we get that \[ -18 = a \cdot (6)(-3) \implies a = 1 \] Hence inputting this value of \(a\) into our equation and expanding the brackets we obtain \[ y = x^2+3x -18. \]
